properties.Title: Update To Civil Emergency Alert Issued By Government Of Saskatchewan
properties.Summary:
Description: Update for the Civil Emergency Alert issued by the Government of Saskatchewan. The state of emergency in Saskatchewan remains in effect. UPDATE: Phase 1 of Re-Open Saskatchewan is effective May 4, 2020. All Public Health Orders will continue to apply during implementation of Phase 1 Re-Open Saskatchewan. Updated allowable services on Phase 1 for the Northern Village of La Loche and the City of Lloydminster, can be found on the COVID 19 website at Saskatchewan.ca under Public Health Orders, Bullet Number 2, List of Critical Public Services and Allowable Business Services. Continue to practice physical distancing. Avoid gatherings with people outside your immediate household. Avoid unnecessary travel. Self-isolate if returning from foreign travel or if experiencing any symptoms. Wash your hands often. Together, we are reducing the risk. We can pull together by staying apart.
Expires: 2020-05-11T17:00:00-06:00

properties.Title: Frost Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Frost may damage some crops in frost-prone areas. Temperatures will drop to near or below the freezing mark overnight tonight. The relatively cool weather for this time of the year will last several more days. As a result, the frost advisory for Southwestern Quebec may be maintained for all nights and mornings through the rest of this week, possibly into Saturday morning. ### Frost advisories are issued when temperatures are expected to reach the freezing mark during the growing season, leading to potential damage and destruction to plants and crops. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall tonight. Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm. Time span: continuing until early Wednesday morning. Locations: The Great Northern Peninsula. Remarks: The most significant accumulations will likely occur inland and over higher terrain where temperatures will generally be cooler than along the coast. Along the coast, snow will be wet or possibly mixed with rain throughout the event. The snow will change to rain over all areas Wednesday morning before tapering to flurries or rain showers by noon. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall expected today into this evening. Total snowfall: 10 to 15 cm. Time span: continuing until near midnight tonight. Locations: Green Bay - White Bay, Deer Lake, Buchans and vicinity. Remarks: Snow will become mixed with ice pellets or freezing rain this afternoon. Snowfall accumulations should be highest inland and over higher terrain where temperatures will remain cooler. Precipitation will change to a mixture of rain and freezing rain tonight before tapering to flurries or rain showers early on Wednesday. No major ice accumulation from freezing rain is expected at this time. However, motorists that must travel are advised to prepare for slippery road conditions in case icing does become an issue. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
